              <h2>Profitability Index Formula</h2>
              <p>
                The <strong>profitability index (PI)</strong> measures the value
                created per unit of investment. It is widely used in capital
                budgeting to rank and select projects, especially when capital
                is limited.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Standard definition (single initial outlay at t = 0):
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{PI} = \frac{\text{PV of future cash
                  inflows}}{\text{Initial investment}} \]
                </p>
                <p>Where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    Initial investment is usually a positive number in the
                    denominator (we use its absolute value).
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Future cash inflows are discounted at the project’s required
                    rate of return.
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2 font-semibold mb-1">
                  Generalized definition (multiple outflows over time):
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{PI} = \frac{\text{PV of all positive cash
                  flows}}{\text{PV of all negative cash flows}} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                In terms of <strong>net present value (NPV)</strong> and initial
                investment \( I_0 \):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ \text{NPV} = \sum_{t=0}^{T} \frac{CF_t}{(1+r)^t} \]</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{PI} = \frac{\text{NPV} + I_0}{I_0}
                  \quad\Rightarrow\quad \text{PI} = 1 + \frac{\text{NPV}}{I_0}
                  \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>How to Use the Profitability Index Calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the discount rate</strong> – typically your
                  <em>cost of capital</em> or required return (e.g., 10%).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Set the number of periods</strong> (years) and click
                  <em>Apply</em> to create the cash flow rows.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter cash flows</strong>:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Year 0 is usually the
                      <strong>initial investment</strong> (negative cash flow).
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Later years are typically
                      <strong>net cash inflows</strong> (positive), but can also
                      be outflows.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Use the <strong>Type</strong> dropdown to mark each row as
                      an <em>Inflow</em> or <em>Outflow</em> for the generalized
                      PI definition.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>Calculate PI</strong> to compute:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Profitability index (PI)</li>
                    <li>Net present value (NPV)</li>
                    <li>Present value of inflows and outflows</li>
                    <li>
                      A clear <strong>accept / reject</strong> recommendation
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Optionally, click <strong>Export CSV</strong> to download the
                  full cash flow and discounting table.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Decision Rule for Profitability Index</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>PI &gt; 1.0</strong> → Accept the project (it creates
                  value).
                </li>
                <li><strong>PI = 1.0</strong> → Break-even in NPV terms.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>PI &lt; 1.0</strong> → Reject the project (it destroys
                  value).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For <strong>mutually exclusive projects</strong> with no capital
                constraint, PI and NPV give the same accept/reject decision, but
                <strong>NPV</strong> is preferred for ranking. Under
                <strong>capital rationing</strong> (limited budget), PI is very
                useful to rank projects by “NPV per dollar invested”.
              </p>

              <h3>Example</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose a project requires an initial investment of \$100,000
                and generates the following cash inflows at a 10% discount rate:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Year 1: \$40,000</li>
                <li>Year 2: \$40,000</li>
                <li>Year 3: \$40,000</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Present value of inflows:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ PV_{\text{inflows}} = \frac{40{,}000}{1.1^1} +
                  \frac{40{,}000}{1.1^2} + \frac{40{,}000}{1.1^3} \approx
                  36{,}364 + 33{,}058 + 30{,}053 = 99{,}475 \]
                </p>
                <p>\[ \text{PI} = \frac{99{,}475}{100{,}000} \approx 0.99 \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Because PI &lt; 1, the project would be
                <strong>rejected</strong> at a 10% required return.
              </p>

              <h2>Advantages and Limitations of Profitability Index</h2>
              <h3>Advantages</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Time value of money</strong> – uses discounted cash
                  flows, unlike simple payback.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Scale-free</strong> – expresses value per unit of
                  investment, useful for ranking projects when capital is
                  limited.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consistent with NPV</strong> – PI &gt; 1 if and only
                  if NPV &gt; 0 (under the standard definition).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Limitations</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ranking conflicts with NPV</strong> – for mutually
                  exclusive projects of different sizes, PI and NPV can rank
                  projects differently.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Requires a discount rate</strong> – results are
                  sensitive to the chosen cost of capital.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Assumes conventional cash flows</strong> – multiple
                  sign changes can make interpretation less straightforward.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

              <h3>Is profitability index better than NPV?</h3>
              <p>
                Neither is universally “better”. <strong>NPV</strong> is the
                gold standard for measuring absolute value creation.
                <strong>PI</strong> is especially helpful when you must choose
                among many projects under a <strong>capital budget</strong>,
                because it shows value created per dollar invested.
              </p>

              <h3>Can PI be negative?</h3>
              <p>
                Under the standard definition, PI is rarely expressed as a
                negative number; instead, values below 1.0 indicate that NPV is
                negative. If you use the generalized definition with unusual
                cash flow patterns, a negative PI is mathematically possible but
                not commonly reported in practice.
              </p>

              <h3>What discount rate should I use?</h3>
              <p>
                Use the project’s
                <strong>weighted average cost of capital (WACC)</strong> or your
                required rate of return for that risk class. Higher discount
                rates penalize distant cash flows more heavily and will reduce
                both NPV and PI.
              </p>
